alized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9954179525375366, "span": {"begin": 934, "end": 937}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005047"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "etoposide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9532608985900879, "span": {"begin": 1142, "end": 1151}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:7157"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "p53", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.994023859500885, "span": {"begin": 1230, "end": 1233}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target cell model", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9319179654121399, "span": {"begin": 1274, "end": 1291}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "target cell", "obj": "cell_type", "prob": 0.5061472654342651, "span": {"begin": 1274, "end": 1285}}, {"id": ["mesh:D005047"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "etoposide", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.980130672454834, "span": {"begin": 1345, "end": 1354}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human fetal liver CD34+ cells", "obj": "cell_line", "prob": 0.9602759480476379, "span": {"begin": 1462, "end": 1491}}, {"id": ["NCBITaxon:9606"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "human", "obj": "species", "prob": 0.9655905961990356, "span": {"begin": 1462, "end": 1467}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:947"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "CD34+", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.6609076261520386, "span": {"begin": 1480, "end": 1485}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "micro;M and", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5822569727897644, "span": {"begin": 1553, "end": 1564}}, {"id": ["CUI-less"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MLL translocations", "obj": "DNA", "prob": 0.5147528648376465, "span": {"begin": 1565, "end": 1583}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:4297"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "MLL", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.5678865909576416, "span": {"begin": 1565, "end": 1568}}], "text": "A type II topoisomerase can introduce negative supercoils into DNA, all known eukaryotic cells can only relax DNA. The decatenation of interlocked DNA is a critical topoisomerase function, since semi-conservative DNA replication results in catenated sister chromatids. Topoisomerases are important targets for many chemotherapeutic agents. These agents convert their target topoisomerases to DNA-damaging agents. The DNA is cut in both strands and the agents prevent the subsequent DNA-resealing step normally catalyzed by topoisomerases (Nitiss 2009).  Molecular dose-response modelling of etoposide-induced DNA damage response, based on comprehensive in vitro high content imaging in the HT1080 cell model, was developed by Li et al (2014). The model was based on the hypothesis that cells are capable of clearing low-level DNA damage with existing repair capacity, but when the number of DSBs exceeds a certain value,&nbsp;ATM and p53 become fully activated through reversible mechanism, leading to elevated repair capacity. The model was able to capture quantitatively the dose-response relationships of a number of markers observed with etoposide. Especially interesting are the dose-response relationships for activation of p53 and the formation of micronuclei in the target cell model, which indicate point-of-departure concentrations of etoposide in the range of 0.01 to 0.1 &micro;M (Li et al. 2014). This range is in agreement with the finding that in human fetal liver CD34+ cells an increase in DSBs was observed at a concentration of 0.14 &micro;M and MLL translocations were detectable by FISH or flow cytometry at higher concentrations (Moneypenny et al 2006).", "timestamp": "Mon Jun 08 14:59:59 +0000 2026"}